The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Buses off, bytes

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Calcutta, Dec. 11: CPM labour arm Citu will reveal tomorrow which industries it will exempt from Thursdays nationwide strike. 

 Its general secretary, Chittabrata Majumdar, said whether Bengals IT sector, which Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee wants spared, would shut down depended on its employees. 

 The Bengal chief minister had assured IT and ITES companies they would be left out of the strikes ambit. 

 Majumdar said: We have not exempted the IT sector. But strikes are not enforced in any industry. In IT, too, we would depend on employees spontaneous involvement. 

 He added, though, that all forms of mass transport would be paralysed that day. 

 Although nationwide, the strike is likely to have a serious impact only in Left-ruled Bengal, Kerala and Tripura.

 Bengal IT minister Debesh Das was evasive on whether the IT companies in Bhattacharjees showpiece Sector V would be able to work normally on December 14. The government will neither force anybody to work nor allow anybody to coerce people to join the strike.

 Transport minister Subhas Chakraborty announced that no public or private transport would ply in Bengal on strike day.

 State Citu president Shyamal Chakraborty made it clear that the union was gearing up for a total shutdown. 

 This time, we are not issuing car stickers to IT companies to avoid trouble on the road, Das said. 

 Stickers meant to ensure vehicles would be let through had earlier made them a favourite target for bandh enforcers. 




